Having established that fluorescence emission was more significantly quenched by Cr6+ ions than by other metal ions, the sensitivity towards the Cr6+ ion was evaluated. Fig. 7
                           a shows the fluorescence spectra following addition of Cr6+ ions in aqueous solution, at concentrations from 0 µM to 100 µM. As the concentration of Cr6+ ions increased, the fluorescence intensity of the carbon dots decreased. Fig. 7b shows the relationship between F/F0 and Cr6+ ion concentration. As the concentration of Cr6+ ion was increased from 0 to 100 μM, linear fits with coefficients of determination R2 = 0.9903 and a linear range from 1 to 100 µM were obtained, confirming the static quenching mechanism. In addition, the limit of detection (LOD), calculated using the 3σ/slope method, where σ is the standard deviation [64], produced a value of 0.73 µM, comparable to those reported in previous studies (Table 1
                           ). In contrast to previous reports, our carbon dots were not functionalized, but showed comparable sensitivity. Accordingly, the guideline maximum limit proposed by the World Health Organization (WHO) for Cr6+ concentrations is 0.96 μM in drinking water [53]. Our carbon dots were therefore capable of detecting the Cr6+ concentration at the reference level.

The electronic nose (Fig. 8
                           ) is an artificial device for detection of odors and vapors that is used in environmental monitoring, quality and safety control, and military applications. The optical electronic nose utilizes a sensing material that interacts with vapors, producing a change in optical properties that can be detected and processed into a signal. Although the hydrophilicity and strong absorption in the UV–visible region of the carbon dots made them a strong candidate sensing material for detection of VOCs in an optical electronic nose. The carbon dot-integrated nose was exposed to VOCs using nitrogen gas as a reference and carrier. Methanol (MeOH), ethanol (EtOH), dichloromethane (DCM), tetrahydrofuran (THF), and hexane were used as analytes. The dynamic response of the film to a change in light intensity was measured as a function of time, as the VOC vapor was switched on and off repeatedly. When the VOCs, especially methanol, ethanol, and dichloromethane, were flowed through the thin film, the sensor response decreased rapidly with different magnitudes (Fig. 9
                           a). However, the sensor response increased when the nitrogen reference gas was flowed. This suggested that the carbon dots successfully sensed and distinguished the VOC vapors through the change of light transmission through the film. The sensor response was subjected to principal component analysis (PCA). PCA is a statistical tool widely used for reducing high data dimension into linearly uncorrelated variables (principal components, PCs) using orthogonal transformation method. We found no overlap between the PCA score points of the methanol and ethanol, indicating that the carbon dots could differentiate these two alcohols from other VOCs (Fig. 9b). As expected, these two alcohols are the most polar solvents among the tested solvent vapors. This result suggested a strong polar-polar interaction between alcohols and carbon dots, leading to sensing response by optical electronic nose.
